{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9df630c414e3b702", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tThe SonicAGI System for the REAL-TSE Challenge\n2\tKai Li1,2,† , Wendi Sang1,† , Jintao Cheng1 , Xiaolin Hu1,2,3,∗\n3\t\n4\tarXiv:2607.11083v1 [cs.SD] 13 Jul 2026\n5\t\n6\t1\n7\t\n8\tDepartment of Computer Science and Technology, Institute for AI, BNRist, Tsinghua University, Beijing, China\n9\t2\n10\tIDG/McGovern Institute for Brain Research, Tsinghua University, Beijing, China\n11\t3\n12\tChinese Institute for Brain Research (CIBR), Beijing, China\n13\t†\n14\tThese authors contributed equally to this work. ∗ Corresponding author.\n15\t\n16\tAbstract—Real-world target speaker extraction (TSE) remains challenging because target speech, interference, and enrollment are recorded\n17\tunder mismatched acoustic conditions with reverberation, noise, and\n18\tirregular conversational overlap. This paper describes the SonicAGI\n19\tsubmission to the REAL-TSE Challenge (IEEE SLT 2026). We take a\n20\tdata-centric approach that combines fully simulated mixtures from clean\n21\tspeech with real meeting overlaps, and use a frozen offline enhancer to\n22\tprovide a denoised mirror of real targets for auxiliary supervision. For the\n23\tonline track, we introduce SwiftNet-Lookahead, which inserts a single\n24\tbounded-lookahead module before a strictly causal iterative separator\n25\tand keeps the total system latency at 96 ms. For the offline track, we\n26\tuse a frame-level enrollment cross-attention USEF-TFGridNet with a\n27\tmagnitude-domain fusion stage that trades off perceptual quality and\n28\tspeaker fidelity. In the official evaluation, SwiftNet-Lookahead ranks\n29\tsecond in Track 1 and USEF-TFGridNet ranks fifth in Track 2, both\n30\texceeding the challenge baselines. These results suggest that real-dataoriented training and track-specific modeling are effective for conversational TSE.\n31\tIndex Terms—target speaker extraction, speech separation, low latency,\n32\tcausal modeling, data simulation, conversational speech\n33\t\n34\tpreserving target-speaker cues. The resulting systems rank second\n35\tin Track 1 and fifth in Track 2, both outperforming the challenge\n36\tbaselines.\n37\tII. DATA C ONSTRUCTION\n38\tAll audio is 16 kHz mono, and training samples are generated on\n39\tthe fly. Each sample takes, with equal probability, one of two routes:\n40\ta Fully Simulated Mixing route that builds the mixture from clean\n41\tspeech under simulated acoustic conditions, and a Real-recording\n42\tMixing route that remixes target and interferer segments cut from\n43\treal meetings. The two routes share the enrollment-length sampling\n44\tand the global-gain setting; enrollment lengths are drawn from [3, 15]\n45\ts (covering 94% of the development-set durations) and the training\n46\tchunk is 3 s. Table I lists the main simulation parameters.\n47\tTABLE I\n48\tK EY DATA - SIMULATION PARAMETERS ( SHARED BY BOTH ROUTES UNLESS\n49\tOTHERWISE NOTED ).\n50\t\n51\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n52\tTarget speaker extraction (TSE) extracts a designated speaker from\n53\ta mixture using an enrollment utterance [1]. It is a key front-end for\n54\thearing aids, meeting transcription, and speech interaction. Although\n55\trecent speech and query-based separation methods perform well on\n56\tcurated or synthetic mixtures [2]–[4], real conversational recordings\n57\tcontain reverberation, background noise, irregular overlap, and crossscene enrollment. These factors expose a persistent mismatch between synthetic training and real evaluation conditions, making data\n58\trealism a central bottleneck.\n59\tThe REAL-TSE Challenge [5] evaluates this setting on real\n60\tMandarin and English meeting and dinner-party recordings, scored\n61\tby transcription error, target-speaker timing, speaker similarity, and\n62\tperceptual quality. Track 1 requires online processing below 100 ms\n63\talgorithmic latency and verifies causality through input-perturbation\n64\ttests, whereas Track 2 allows full-context offline processing. Development data are held-out partitions of AISHELL-4 [6], AliMeeting\n65\t[7], AMI [8], DipCo [9], and CHiME-6 [10]; their development and\n66\ttest splits are excluded from training.\n67\tOur SonicAGI submission is built around three components. First,\n68\twe construct training data with a two-route sampler: Fully Simulated Mixing provides controlled speaker overlap from clean speech,\n69\twhile Real-recording Mixing samples overlapping utterances from\n70\treal meetings; a frozen offline enhancer further produces a cleaned\n71\tmirror of real targets for auxiliary supervision. Second, for Track 1,\n72\twe propose SwiftNet-Lookahead, which inserts a single chunked\n73\tbidirectional LSTM lookahead module before a strictly causal SwiftNet separator, so that future context is available within the latency\n74\tbudget but does not accumulate across iterative updates. Third, for\n75\tTrack 2, we use a frame-level enrollment cross-attention USEFTFGridNet and apply magnitude-domain fusion between the extractor\n76\toutput and its enhanced version, improving perceptual quality while\n77\t\n78\tParameter\n79\t\n80\tValue\n81\t\n82\tSample rate\n83\tFully Simulated / Real-recording Mixing prob.\n84\tTraining chunk length\n85\tEnrollment length\n86\tNumber of speakers N\n87\tSignal-to-interference ratio\n88\tNoise probability (synthetic)\n89\tNoise SNR (synthetic)\n90\tReverberation RT60 (synthetic)\n91\tGlobal gain\n92\tCross-scene enrollment prob. (real)\n93\tSamples per epoch\n94\t\n95\t16 kHz, mono\n96\t0.5 / 0.5\n97\t3.0 s\n98\t[3, 15] s\n99\t2–4\n100\t[−5, 10] dB\n101\t0.6\n102\t[−5, 25] dB\n103\t[0.1, 0.7] s\n104\t[−12, 0] dB\n105\t0.5\n106\t20,000\n107\t\n108\tA. Source corpora\n109\tThe Fully Simulated Mixing route draws clean single-speaker\n110\tspeech from LRS3 [11] and VoxCeleb2 [12], transcoded from mp4\n111\tto PCM WAV. The Real-recording Mixing route draws overlapping\n112\tspeech from the official training splits of AISHELL-4 [6], AliMeeting [7], AMI [8] (single distant microphone), and CHiME-6 [10].\n113\tFollowing the challenge rules, we exclude the development and test\n114\tsets of every corpus, and never use DipCo for training. WHAM!\n115\t[13] noise serves as the additive background in the Fully Simulated\n116\tMixing route.\n117\tB. Fully Simulated Mixing route\n118\tA Fully Simulated Mixing sample first selects a target speaker\n119\tand an anchor utterance, then draws N ∈ [2, 4] speakers in total\n120\t(of which N − 1 interferers come from the full speaker pool), and\n121\treverberates each source with an independent single-channel room\n122\timpulse response generated by a fast random-image simulator [14]\n123\t(RT60 in [0.1, 0.7] s). Interferers are added at a signal-to-interference\n124\t\n125\t\fratio in [−5, 10] dB; the mixture is peak-normalized jointly with\n126\tthe sources, an optional global gain in [−12, 0] dB is applied, and\n127\tfinally WHAM! noise is added with probability 0.6 at [−5, 25] dB.\n128\tThe enrollment uses another utterance of the target speaker, and is\n129\tdegraded independently of the mixture with its own room impulse\n130\tresponse (probability 0.5) and additive noise (probability 0.5, [0, 20]\n131\tdB), so that the model cannot use a shared acoustic channel as a\n132\tshortcut cue for identifying the target.\n133\tC. Real-recording Mixing route\n134\tA Real-recording Mixing sample is drawn entirely from one\n135\tmeeting: the target and one or more interferers are real utterances\n136\tfrom the same recording, so the mixture keeps genuine acoustics\n137\tand we add no artificial reverberation or noise [15]. Interferers are\n138\tremixed at a signal-to-interference ratio in [−5, 10] dB, followed\n139\tby the same peak normalization and optional global gain. With\n140\tprobability 0.5 the enrollment prefers a cross-scene reference (the\n141\tsame speaker in another meeting), falling back to a same-scene one\n142\totherwise; this suppresses the model’s shortcut dependence on the\n143\tacoustic environment and matches the cross-meeting enrollment of\n144\tthe evaluation set.\n145\tReal meeting segments are never perfectly clean: the “target”\n146\tstill contains background noise and crosstalk. To use these segments without forcing the network to reproduce that noise, we precompute a cleaned mirror of the real corpora with a frozen offline\n147\tenhancer (RE-USE [16]). The mixture is always built from the noisy\n148\t(acoustically real) target, while the enrollment is loaded from the\n149\tcleaned mirror. For the offline USEF-TFGridNet, the two views\n150\tform a combined supervision target (noisy as the primary term,\n151\tcleaned as a light auxiliary) that keeps the acoustic mapping faithful\n152\tto the real target while improving perceptual quality; weights are\n153\tgiven in Section IV. To ensure training stability, the online SwiftNetLookahead is supervised only with the noisy real target.\n154\tIII. S YSTEMS\n155\tBoth tracks use the data pipeline above, but differ in separator\n156\tarchitecture and enrollment conditioning.\n157\tA. Online track: SwiftNet-Lookahead\n158\tFor Track 1, SwiftNet-Lookahead introduces bounded future context into a causal TSE model. Its backbone is a weight-shared SwiftNet [17] separator with twelve iterative updates, each combining\n159\tmulti-scale causal convolutions, frequency-axis bidirectional modeling, time-axis unidirectional modeling, and causally masked selfattention. A frozen ResNet-34 speaker encoder [18] from WeSpeaker\n160\t[19] provides the target representation, which is injected by featurewise linear modulation (FiLM) [20] only at the first iteration; subsequent updates refine the same conditioned representation. The STFT\n161\tfront end uses a 256-point window and 128-sample hop, adding only\n162\tthe analysis-synthesis delay.\n163\tA naive lookahead inside each shared update would accumulate:\n164\tn future frames per update would become 12n frames after twelve\n165\titerations. We instead insert a single LookaheadModule between the\n166\taudio bottleneck and the causal separator. It partitions time into nonoverlapping chunks of length S and applies a bidirectional LSTM\n167\tindependently within each chunk; the output is projected, layernormalized, and added as a residual. Because no recurrent state\n168\tcrosses chunk boundaries, the maximum future context is\n169\tlookaheadmax = (S − 1) H,\n170\t\n171\t(1)\n172\t\n173\twhere H is the STFT hop. The separator remains strictly causal, so no\n174\tadditional lookahead accumulates. We use a two-layer bidirectional\n175\t\n176\tLSTM with 128 hidden units per direction on the 256-channel\n177\tbottleneck. With S = 11 and H = 128 samples (8 ms/frame), the\n178\tmaximum lookahead is 80 ms.\n179\tUnder the challenge latency definition, the algorithmic latency is\n180\tthe 8 ms STFT delay plus the 80 ms lookahead, yielding 88 ms;\n181\tincluding the 8 ms hop buffer gives 96 ms total system latency.\n182\tThe streaming schedule emits one hop after the corresponding\n183\tbounded-lookahead chunk is available, and no recurrent state carries\n184\tfuture information across chunks. A tail-perturbation probe reported\n185\teffective lookaheads of 37.9, 75.0, and 22.6 ms at three positions, all\n186\tbelow the structural bound in Eq. (1); these spot checks supplement,\n187\tbut do not replace, the architectural latency bound.\n188\tB. Offline track: USEF-TFGridNet\n189\tFor Track 2, we use full-context modeling with a USEF-style\n190\tTFGridNet extractor [21], [22]. Rather than compressing the enrollment into a fixed-dimensional speaker embedding, the model\n191\tkeeps frame-level enrollment features and conditions the mixture\n192\tthrough per-frequency cross-attention, with mixture frames as queries\n193\tand effective enrollment frames as keys and values. Since padded\n194\tenrollment frames are excluded from the keys and values, conditioning is invariant to in-batch padding. The target-aware representation\n195\tis concatenated with the mixture representation, processed by six\n196\tGridNetV2 blocks, and decoded by a transposed convolution followed\n197\tby an inverse STFT. The model uses a 256-point window, a 128sample hop, a shared encoder with C = 128 channels, four attention\n198\theads, and GridNetV2 blocks with hidden dimension 256.\n199\tAfter extraction, we apply a validation-tuned magnitude-domain\n200\tfusion to balance perceptual quality and speaker fidelity. Let xr , xe ∈\n201\tRN denote the original extractor output and the output after a frozen\n202\tRE-USE [16] enhancer for the same sample. The enhanced output\n203\tsuppresses noise but can attenuate the target, whereas the original\n204\toutput preserves target-speaker cues but retains residual noise. We\n205\ttherefore align RMS, fuse STFT magnitudes, and reuse the phase of\n206\txr .\n207\tSpecifically, we first align the RMS of the enhanced output to that\n208\tof the original output:\n209\t\u0012\n210\t\u0013\n211\trms(xr )\n212\tx̃e = g xe , g = clip\n213\t, 0.1, 10 .\n214\t(2)\n215\trms(xe )\n216\tLet Xr = STFT(xr ) and Xe = STFT(x̃e ), with magnitudes\n217\tMr = |Xr | and Me = |Xe |. We estimate frame-level speech activity\n218\tfrom the enhanced magnitude:\n219\t!\n220\ts\n221\tt +ϵ\n222\t20 log10 pe20\n223\t−τ\n224\t1 X\n225\t+ϵ\n226\t2\n227\tet =\n228\tMe (f, t) , at = σ\n229\t, (3)\n230\tF\n231\t∆\n232\tf\n233\t\n234\twhere p20 is the 20th-percentile energy of {et }, τ = 10 dB is the\n235\tactivity threshold above this floor, ∆ = 6 dB controls the sigmoid\n236\ttransition width, and ϵ is a small constant. We smooth at with a 5frame moving average to obtain ãt , and compute the fused magnitude\n237\tas\n238\twt = w − ρãt ,\n239\t\n240\tMf (f, t) = wt Me (f, t) + (1 − wt )Mr (f, t).\n241\t(4)\n242\tHere w is the background-frame enhancement weight and ρ reduces\n243\tthis weight on speech-active frames. We use validation-tuned values\n244\tw = 0.9 and ρ = 0.35, so active frames retain more of the\n245\toriginal TSE magnitude (w − ρ = 0.55) while background frames\n246\tremain closer to the enhanced magnitude. The final waveform is\n247\treconstructed as\n248\tx̂ = iSTFT(Mf exp (j∠Xr )) .\n249\t\n250\t(5)\n251\t\n252\t\fIV. T RAINING S ETUP\n253\tBoth systems were trained with the same protocol: gradient clipping at norm 5.0 and a plateau learning-rate scheduler (decay factor\n254\t0.5) driven by the scale-invariant SNR on a validation set of heldout meetings with scenes disjoint from training. Checkpoint selection\n255\tand early stopping both followed this validation metric, avoiding any\n256\ttuning with leaderboard feedback.\n257\tThe track-specific configurations differed in supervision and optimizer. SwiftNet-Lookahead minimized a plain SNR loss against the\n258\ttarget speech, with its ResNet-34 speaker encoder frozen, and was\n259\ttrained on six GPUs with AdamW (initial learning rate 10−3 , weight\n260\tdecay 0.1). USEF-TFGridNet used a combined SNR loss weighting\n261\tthe noisy real target by 0.8 and the cleaned mirror by 0.2, and was\n262\toptimized by Adam [23] with an initial learning rate of 5 × 10−4 .\n263\tAll external corpora and frozen checkpoints used by the submission\n264\tare named in Sections II–III; no development or evaluation split is\n265\tused for training, fine-tuning, or data augmentation.\n266\tV. R ESULTS\n267\tEvaluation protocol. The evaluation set comprises EVAL-1 (2000\n268\t“seen” mixture–enrollment pairs drawn without overlap from the development corpora) and EVAL-2 (3000 “unseen” real-world samples\n269\tnewly recorded across meeting rooms, cafés, homes, and vehicles\n270\twith near-field, far-field, and mobile devices). Each pair was processed independently with all metadata withheld. The leaderboard\n271\tscores four metrics: target-speaker error rate (TER; lower is better),\n272\tpresence-timing F1, speaker similarity (SIM, cosine), and DNSMOS\n273\t[24] perceptual quality. The official rank is the average dense rank\n274\tover these four metrics on the combined EVAL-1+EVAL-2 target;\n275\tthe public leaderboard1 listed 28 Track 1 participants and 35 Track 2\n276\tparticipants at our final snapshot [5].\n277\tOnline track. Table II reports Track 1. On the public leaderboard\n278\tsnapshot, SwiftNet-Lookahead ranks second overall among valid\n279\tparticipants. The table compares it with the two official BSRNN\n280\tbaselines [25]; SwiftNet-Lookahead leads both on all four metrics.\n281\tThe ablation in Table III explains two design choices. For training\n282\tdata, the mixed setting attains the best TER, Timing F1, and SIM;\n283\tsynthetic-only data degrades the most (TER 0.857, DNSMOS 1.676),\n284\tsuggesting that real acoustics are important for generalization, while\n285\treal-only data reaches a marginally higher DNSMOS but trails on\n286\tintelligibility and similarity, being limited in scale and scene diversity.\n287\tFor the enrollment encoder, ResNet-34 gives the best TER and the\n288\tbest DNSMOS; TF-MAP/contextual embedding [26] matches it on\n289\tTiming F1 and SIM but drops sharply to 1.923 DNSMOS, and\n290\tECAPA-TDNN [27] is comparable on TER yet weaker elsewhere. We\n291\ttherefore adopt mixed training data with the ResNet-34 conditioning\n292\trepresentation.\n293\tTABLE II\n294\tO NLINE TRACK (T RACK 1).\n295\t\n296\tSystem\n297\t\n298\tTER↓ Timing F1↑ SIM↑ DNSMOS↑\n299\t\n300\tSwiftNet-Lookahead (ours) 0.719\n301\tBSRNN-TFMAP\n302\t0.805\n303\tBSRNN-EMB\n304\t0.809\n305\t\n306\t0.847\n307\t0.836\n308\t0.821\n309\t\n310\t0.480\n311\t0.456\n312\t0.422\n313\t\n314\t2.399\n315\t1.670\n316\t1.714\n317\t\n318\tOffline track. Table IV reports Track 2. USEF-TFGridNet ranks\n319\tfifth on the public snapshot and beats both baselines by a large margin\n320\t(TER 0.680, DNSMOS 2.484). Its remaining speaker-similarity gap\n321\tis consistent with the perception-distortion trade-off from fusing\n322\t1 https://leaderboard.real-tse.com/\n323\t\n324\tTABLE III\n325\tA BLATION STUDY OF S WIFT N ET-L OOKAHEAD .\n326\t\n327\tConfiguration\n328\t\n329\tTER↓ Timing F1↑ SIM↑ DNSMOS↑\n330\t\n331\tTraining-data composition\n332\tMixed synthetic + real (default) 0.719\n333\tSynthetic data only\n334\t0.857\n335\tReal data only\n336\t0.739\n337\t\n338\t0.847\n339\t0.839\n340\t0.841\n341\t\n342\t0.480\n343\t0.454\n344\t0.450\n345\t\n346\t2.399\n347\t1.676\n348\t2.477\n349\t\n350\tEnrollment audio encoder\n351\tResNet-34 (default)\n352\t0.719\n353\tECAPA-TDNN\n354\t0.723\n355\tTF-MAP/contextual embedding 0.757\n356\t\n357\t0.847\n358\t0.828\n359\t0.848\n360\t\n361\t0.480\n362\t0.464\n363\t0.483\n364\t\n365\t2.399\n366\t2.392\n367\t1.923\n368\t\n369\ttoward denoised magnitudes on background frames [28]. Table V\n370\tshows that frame-level enrollment cross-attention gives the best TER\n371\tand DNSMOS, whereas compressed embeddings have similar Timing\n372\tF1/SIM but worse perceptual quality. Within the supervision-weight\n373\tblock, 0.8:0.2 is best on all metrics; a small cleaned-mirror weight\n374\tbalances fidelity to real acoustics against residual-noise suppression.\n375\tTABLE IV\n376\tO FFLINE TRACK (T RACK 2).\n377\t\n378\tSystem\n379\t\n380\tTER↓ Timing F1↑ SIM↑ DNSMOS↑\n381\t\n382\tUSEF-TFGridNet (ours)\n383\t0.680\n384\tBSRNN-EMB (baseline)\n385\t0.829\n386\tBSRNN-TFMAP (baseline) 0.838\n387\t\n388\t0.851\n389\t0.829\n390\t0.829\n391\t\n392\t0.471\n393\t0.417\n394\t0.443\n395\t\n396\t2.484\n397\t1.844\n398\t1.612\n399\t\n400\tTABLE V\n401\tA BLATION STUDY OF USEF-TFG RID N ET.\n402\t\n403\tConfiguration\n404\t\n405\tTER↓ Timing F1↑ SIM↑ DNSMOS↑\n406\t\n407\tEnrollment audio encoder\n408\tUSEF (default)\n409\t0.680\n410\tResNet-34\n411\t0.739\n412\tECAPA-TDNN\n413\t0.728\n414\tTF-MAP/contextual embedding 0.781\n415\t\n416\t0.851\n417\t0.853\n418\t0.850\n419\t0.845\n420\t\n421\t0.471\n422\t0.474\n423\t0.476\n424\t0.470\n425\t\n426\t2.484\n427\t1.903\n428\t2.248\n429\t2.138\n430\t\n431\tCombined supervision weight (noisy real target:cleaned mirror target)\n432\t0:1\n433\t0.756\n434\t0.844\n435\t0.454\n436\t2.271\n437\t0.5 : 0.5\n438\t0.739\n439\t0.841\n440\t0.450\n441\t2.477\n442\t0.8 : 0.2 (default)\n443\t0.680\n444\t0.851\n445\t0.471\n446\t2.484\n447\t1:0\n448\t0.684\n449\t0.840\n450\t0.452\n451\t2.249\n452\t\n453\tVI. C ONCLUSION\n454\tThis paper presents the SonicAGI systems for the online and offline\n455\ttracks of the REAL-TSE Challenge. The results suggest that real\n456\tconversational TSE depends not only on separator design, but also\n457\ton training-data realism and target construction. Our two-route data\n458\tpipeline combines controllable synthetic mixtures with real meeting\n459\toverlap, and uses a cleaned mirror target to reduce the effect of\n460\tresidual background noise in real recordings. SwiftNet-Lookahead\n461\tconfines future context to a single bounded injection, achieving\n462\tsecond place in Track 1 with 96 ms total system latency. USEFTFGridNet combines frame-level enrollment cross-attention with\n463\tmagnitude-domain fusion, ranking fifth in Track 2 while improving\n464\tintelligibility and perceptual quality. The main remaining limitation is\n465\tthe trade-off between speaker similarity and perceptual quality; future\n466\twork will explore similarity-aware training or fusion objectives and\n467\textend bounded lookahead to stronger cross-attention extractors.\n468\t\n469\t\fAI-G ENERATED C ONTENT D ISCLOSURE\n470\tChatGPT was used to assist with language editing, grammar refinement, and concision of the manuscript text. The authors reviewed\n471\tand revised all AI-assisted edits.\n472\tR EFERENCES\n473\t[1] S. Wang, Z. Chen, K. A. Lee, Y. Qian, and H. Li, “Overview of\n474\tspeaker modeling and its applications: From the lens of deep speaker\n475\trepresentation learning,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and\n476\tLanguage Processing, vol. 32, pp. 4971–4998, 2024.\n477\t[2] K. Li, G. Chen, W. Sang, Y. Luo, Z. Chen, S. Wang, S. He, Z.-Q.\n478\tWang, A. Li, Z. Wu et al., “Advances in speech separation: Techniques,\n479\tchallenges, and future trends,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2508.10830, 2025.\n480\t[3] K. Li, K. Gao, and X. Hu, “Efficient audio-visual speech separation\n481\twith discrete lip semantics and multi-scale global-local attention,” arXiv\n482\tpreprint arXiv:2509.23610, 2025.\n483\t[4] K. Li, J. Cheng, C. Zeng, Z. Yan, H. Wang, Z. Su, B. Zheng, and\n484\tX. Hu, “A semantically consistent dataset for data-efficient query-based\n485\tuniversal sound separation,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2601.22599, 2026.\n486\t[5] REAL-TSE Challenge Organizers, “REAL-TSE Challenge: Realworld Target Speaker Extraction Challenge,” https://real-tse.github.io/\n487\tchallenge/, 2026, a satellite challenge of IEEE Spoken Language Technology Workshop (SLT) 2026. Accessed: 2026-06-29.\n488\t[6] Y. Fu, L. Cheng, S. Lv, Y. Jv, Y. Kong, Z. Chen, Y. Hu, L. Xie, J. Wu,\n489\tH. Bu, X. Xu, J. Du, and J. Chen, “AISHELL-4: An open source dataset\n490\tfor speech enhancement, separation, recognition and speaker diarization\n491\tin conference scenario,” in Annual Conference of the International\n492\tSpeech Communication Association (Interspeech), 2021, pp. 3665–3669.\n493\t[7] F. Yu, S. Zhang, Y. Fu, L. Xie, S. Zheng, Z. Du, W. Huang, P. Guo,\n494\tZ. Yan, B. Ma, X. Xu, and H. Bu, “M2MeT: The ICASSP 2022\n495\tmulti-channel multi-party meeting transcription challenge,” in IEEE\n496\tInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n497\t(ICASSP), 2022, pp. 6167–6171.\n498\t[8] J. Carletta, S. Ashby, S. Bourban, M. Flynn, M. Guillemot, T. Hain,\n499\tJ. Kadlec, V. Karaiskos, W. Kraaij, M. Kronenthal, G. Lathoud, M. Lincoln, A. Lisowska, I. McCowan, W. Post, D. Reidsma, and P. Wellner,\n500\t“The AMI meeting corpus: A pre-announcement,” in Machine Learning\n501\tfor Multimodal Interaction. Springer Berlin Heidelberg, 2006, pp. 28–\n502\t39.\n503\t[9] M. Van Segbroeck, A. Zaid, K. Kutsenko, C. Huerta, T. Nguyen,\n504\tX. Luo, B. Hoffmeister, J. Trmal, M. Omologo, and R. Maas, “DiPCo –\n505\tdinner party corpus,” in Annual Conference of the International Speech\n506\tCommunication Association (Interspeech), 2020, pp. 434–438.\n507\t[10] S. Watanabe, M. Mandel, J. Barker, E. Vincent, A. Arora, X. Chang,\n508\tS. Khudanpur, V. Manohar, D. Povey, D. Raj, D. Snyder, A. S. Subramanian, J. Trmal, B. B. Yair, C. Boeddeker, Z. Ni, Y. Fujita, S. Horiguchi,\n509\tN. Kanda, T. Yoshioka, and N. Ryant, “CHiME-6 challenge: Tackling\n510\tmultispeaker speech recognition for unsegmented recordings,” in 6th\n511\tInternational Workshop on Speech Processing in Everyday Environments\n512\t(CHiME 2020), 2020, pp. 1–7.\n513\t[11] T. Afouras, J. S. Chung, and A. Zisserman, “LRS3-TED: A large-scale\n514\tdataset for visual speech recognition,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1809.00496,\n515\t2018.\n516\t[12] J. S. Chung, A. Nagrani, and A. Zisserman, “VoxCeleb2: Deep speaker\n517\trecognition,” in Annual Conference of the International Speech Communication Association (Interspeech), 2018, pp. 1086–1090.\n518\t[13] G. Wichern, J. Antognini, M. Flynn, L. R. Zhu, E. McQuinn, D. Crow,\n519\tE. Manilow, and J. L. Roux, “WHAM!: Extending speech separation to\n520\tnoisy environments,” in Annual Conference of the International Speech\n521\tCommunication Association (Interspeech), 2019, pp. 1368–1372.\n522\t[14] Y. Luo and J. Yu, “FRA-RIR: Fast random approximation of the imagesource method,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2208.04101, 2022.\n523\t[15] K. Li, W. Sang, C. Zeng, R. Yang, G. Chen, and X. Hu, “Sonicsim:\n524\tA customizable simulation platform for speech processing in moving\n525\tsound source scenarios,” in International Conference on Learning Representations, vol. 2025, 2025, pp. 67 379–67 405.\n526\t[16] S.-W. Fu, R. Chao, X. Yang, S.-F. Huang, R. E. Zezario, R. Nasretdinov,\n527\tA. Jukić, Y. Tsao, and Y.-C. F. Wang, “Rethinking training targets,\n528\tarchitectures and data quality for universal speech enhancement,” arXiv\n529\tpreprint arXiv:2603.02641, 2026.\n530\t[17] W. Sang, K. Li, R. Yang, J. Huang, and X. Hu, “A fast and lightweight\n531\tmodel for causal audio-visual speech separation,” in European Conference on Artificial Intelligence (ECAI), 2025.\n532\t\n533\t[18] K. He, X. Zhang, S. Ren, and J. Sun, “Deep residual learning for\n534\timage recognition,” in IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern\n535\tRecognition (CVPR), 2016, pp. 770–778.\n536\t[19] H. Wang, C. Liang, S. Wang, Z. Chen, B. Zhang, X. Xiang, Y. Deng,\n537\tand Y. Qian, “WeSpeaker: A research and production oriented speaker\n538\tembedding learning toolkit,” in IEEE International Conference on\n539\tAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2023.\n540\t[20] E. Perez, F. Strub, H. de Vries, V. Dumoulin, and A. Courville, “FiLM:\n541\tVisual reasoning with a general conditioning layer,” in AAAI Conference\n542\ton Artificial Intelligence (AAAI), 2018.\n543\t[21] B. Zeng and M. Li, “USEF-TSE: Universal speaker embedding free\n544\ttarget speaker extraction,” IEEE Transactions on Audio, Speech and\n545\tLanguage Processing, vol. 33, pp. 2110–2124, 2025.\n546\t[22] Z.-Q. Wang, S. Cornell, S. Choi, Y. Lee, B.-Y. Kim, and S. Watanabe, “TF-GridNet: Integrating full- and sub-band modeling for speech\n547\tseparation,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language\n548\tProcessing, vol. 31, pp. 3221–3236, 2023.\n549\t[23] D. P. Kingma and J. Ba, “Adam: A method for stochastic optimization,”\n550\tin International Conference on Learning Representations (ICLR), 2015.\n551\t[24] C. K. A. Reddy, V. Gopal, and R. Cutler, “DNSMOS: A non-intrusive\n552\tperceptual objective speech quality metric to evaluate noise suppressors,”\n553\tin IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal\n554\tProcessing (ICASSP), 2021, pp. 6493–6497.\n555\t[25] Y. Luo and J. Yu, “Music source separation with band-split RNN,”\n556\tIEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing,\n557\tvol. 31, pp. 1893–1901, 2023.\n558\t[26] K. Zhang, J. Li, S. Wang, Y. Wei, Y. Wang, Y. Wang, and H. Li, “Multilevel speaker representation for target speaker extraction,” in IEEE\n559\tInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n560\t(ICASSP), 2025.\n561\t[27] B. Desplanques, J. Thienpondt, and K. Demuynck, “ECAPA-TDNN:\n562\tEmphasized channel attention, propagation and aggregation in TDNN\n563\tbased speaker verification,” in Annual Conference of the International\n564\tSpeech Communication Association (Interspeech), 2020, pp. 3830–3834.\n565\t[28] Y. Blau and T. Michaeli, “The perception-distortion tradeoff,” in IEEE\n566\tConference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR), 2018,\n567\tpp. 6228–6237.\n568\t\n569\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "30255bd1-264f-4682-a67a-4161ce2e23bc", "uuid": "179db3e1-5f22-4ccc-b526-4da85d149de8", "timestamp": "2026-07-14T12:24:03.506Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607.11083.txt", "content": "The SonicAGI System for the REAL-TSE Challenge\nKai Li1,2,† , Wendi Sang1,† , Jintao Cheng1 , Xiaolin Hu1,2,3,∗\n\narXiv:2607.11083v1 [cs.SD] 13 Jul 2026\n\n1\n\nDepartment of Computer Science and Technology, Institute for AI, BNRist, Tsinghua University, Beijing, China\n2\nIDG/McGovern Institute for Brain Research, Tsinghua University, Beijing, China\n3\nChinese Institute for Brain Research (CIBR), Beijing, China\n†\nThese authors contributed equally to this work. ∗ Corresponding author.\n\nAbstract—Real-world target speaker extraction (TSE) remains challenging because target speech, interference, and enrollment are recorded\nunder mismatched acoustic conditions with reverberation, noise, and\nirregular conversational overlap. This paper describes the SonicAGI\nsubmission to the REAL-TSE Challenge (IEEE SLT 2026). We take a\ndata-centric approach that combines fully simulated mixtures from clean\nspeech with real meeting overlaps, and use a frozen offline enhancer to\nprovide a denoised mirror of real targets for auxiliary supervision. For the\nonline track, we introduce SwiftNet-Lookahead, which inserts a single\nbounded-lookahead module before a strictly causal iterative separator\nand keeps the total system latency at 96 ms. For the offline track, we\nuse a frame-level enrollment cross-attention USEF-TFGridNet with a\nmagnitude-domain fusion stage that trades off perceptual quality and\nspeaker fidelity. In the official evaluation, SwiftNet-Lookahead ranks\nsecond in Track 1 and USEF-TFGridNet ranks fifth in Track 2, both\nexceeding the challenge baselines. These results suggest that real-dataoriented training and track-specific modeling are effective for conversational TSE.\nIndex Terms—target speaker extraction, speech separation, low latency,\ncausal modeling, data simulation, conversational speech\n\npreserving target-speaker cues. The resulting systems rank second\nin Track 1 and fifth in Track 2, both outperforming the challenge\nbaselines.\nII. DATA C ONSTRUCTION\nAll audio is 16 kHz mono, and training samples are generated on\nthe fly. Each sample takes, with equal probability, one of two routes:\na Fully Simulated Mixing route that builds the mixture from clean\nspeech under simulated acoustic conditions, and a Real-recording\nMixing route that remixes target and interferer segments cut from\nreal meetings. The two routes share the enrollment-length sampling\nand the global-gain setting; enrollment lengths are drawn from [3, 15]\ns (covering 94% of the development-set durations) and the training\nchunk is 3 s. Table I lists the main simulation parameters.\nTABLE I\nK EY DATA - SIMULATION PARAMETERS ( SHARED BY BOTH ROUTES UNLESS\nOTHERWISE NOTED ).\n\nI. I NTRODUCTION\nTarget speaker extraction (TSE) extracts a designated speaker from\na mixture using an enrollment utterance [1]. It is a key front-end for\nhearing aids, meeting transcription, and speech interaction. Although\nrecent speech and query-based separation methods perform well on\ncurated or synthetic mixtures [2]–[4], real conversational recordings\ncontain reverberation, background noise, irregular overlap, and crossscene enrollment. These factors expose a persistent mismatch between synthetic training and real evaluation conditions, making data\nrealism a central bottleneck.\nThe REAL-TSE Challenge [5] evaluates this setting on real\nMandarin and English meeting and dinner-party recordings, scored\nby transcription error, target-speaker timing, speaker similarity, and\nperceptual quality. Track 1 requires online processing below 100 ms\nalgorithmic latency and verifies causality through input-perturbation\ntests, whereas Track 2 allows full-context offline processing. Development data are held-out partitions of AISHELL-4 [6], AliMeeting\n[7], AMI [8], DipCo [9], and CHiME-6 [10]; their development and\ntest splits are excluded from training.\nOur SonicAGI submission is built around three components. First,\nwe construct training data with a two-route sampler: Fully Simulated Mixing provides controlled speaker overlap from clean speech,\nwhile Real-recording Mixing samples overlapping utterances from\nreal meetings; a frozen offline enhancer further produces a cleaned\nmirror of real targets for auxiliary supervision. Second, for Track 1,\nwe propose SwiftNet-Lookahead, which inserts a single chunked\nbidirectional LSTM lookahead module before a strictly causal SwiftNet separator, so that future context is available within the latency\nbudget but does not accumulate across iterative updates. Third, for\nTrack 2, we use a frame-level enrollment cross-attention USEFTFGridNet and apply magnitude-domain fusion between the extractor\noutput and its enhanced version, improving perceptual quality while\n\nParameter\n\nValue\n\nSample rate\nFully Simulated / Real-recording Mixing prob.\nTraining chunk length\nEnrollment length\nNumber of speakers N\nSignal-to-interference ratio\nNoise probability (synthetic)\nNoise SNR (synthetic)\nReverberation RT60 (synthetic)\nGlobal gain\nCross-scene enrollment prob. (real)\nSamples per epoch\n\n16 kHz, mono\n0.5 / 0.5\n3.0 s\n[3, 15] s\n2–4\n[−5, 10] dB\n0.6\n[−5, 25] dB\n[0.1, 0.7] s\n[−12, 0] dB\n0.5\n20,000\n\nA. Source corpora\nThe Fully Simulated Mixing route draws clean single-speaker\nspeech from LRS3 [11] and VoxCeleb2 [12], transcoded from mp4\nto PCM WAV. The Real-recording Mixing route draws overlapping\nspeech from the official training splits of AISHELL-4 [6], AliMeeting [7], AMI [8] (single distant microphone), and CHiME-6 [10].\nFollowing the challenge rules, we exclude the development and test\nsets of every corpus, and never use DipCo for training. WHAM!\n[13] noise serves as the additive background in the Fully Simulated\nMixing route.\nB. Fully Simulated Mixing route\nA Fully Simulated Mixing sample first selects a target speaker\nand an anchor utterance, then draws N ∈ [2, 4] speakers in total\n(of which N − 1 interferers come from the full speaker pool), and\nreverberates each source with an independent single-channel room\nimpulse response generated by a fast random-image simulator [14]\n(RT60 in [0.1, 0.7] s). Interferers are added at a signal-to-interference\n\n\fratio in [−5, 10] dB; the mixture is peak-normalized jointly with\nthe sources, an optional global gain in [−12, 0] dB is applied, and\nfinally WHAM! noise is added with probability 0.6 at [−5, 25] dB.\nThe enrollment uses another utterance of the target speaker, and is\ndegraded independently of the mixture with its own room impulse\nresponse (probability 0.5) and additive noise (probability 0.5, [0, 20]\ndB), so that the model cannot use a shared acoustic channel as a\nshortcut cue for identifying the target.\nC. Real-recording Mixing route\nA Real-recording Mixing sample is drawn entirely from one\nmeeting: the target and one or more interferers are real utterances\nfrom the same recording, so the mixture keeps genuine acoustics\nand we add no artificial reverberation or noise [15]. Interferers are\nremixed at a signal-to-interference ratio in [−5, 10] dB, followed\nby the same peak normalization and optional global gain. With\nprobability 0.5 the enrollment prefers a cross-scene reference (the\nsame speaker in another meeting), falling back to a same-scene one\notherwise; this suppresses the model’s shortcut dependence on the\nacoustic environment and matches the cross-meeting enrollment of\nthe evaluation set.\nReal meeting segments are never perfectly clean: the “target”\nstill contains background noise and crosstalk. To use these segments without forcing the network to reproduce that noise, we precompute a cleaned mirror of the real corpora with a frozen offline\nenhancer (RE-USE [16]). The mixture is always built from the noisy\n(acoustically real) target, while the enrollment is loaded from the\ncleaned mirror. For the offline USEF-TFGridNet, the two views\nform a combined supervision target (noisy as the primary term,\ncleaned as a light auxiliary) that keeps the acoustic mapping faithful\nto the real target while improving perceptual quality; weights are\ngiven in Section IV. To ensure training stability, the online SwiftNetLookahead is supervised only with the noisy real target.\nIII. S YSTEMS\nBoth tracks use the data pipeline above, but differ in separator\narchitecture and enrollment conditioning.\nA. Online track: SwiftNet-Lookahead\nFor Track 1, SwiftNet-Lookahead introduces bounded future context into a causal TSE model. Its backbone is a weight-shared SwiftNet [17] separator with twelve iterative updates, each combining\nmulti-scale causal convolutions, frequency-axis bidirectional modeling, time-axis unidirectional modeling, and causally masked selfattention. A frozen ResNet-34 speaker encoder [18] from WeSpeaker\n[19] provides the target representation, which is injected by featurewise linear modulation (FiLM) [20] only at the first iteration; subsequent updates refine the same conditioned representation. The STFT\nfront end uses a 256-point window and 128-sample hop, adding only\nthe analysis-synthesis delay.\nA naive lookahead inside each shared update would accumulate:\nn future frames per update would become 12n frames after twelve\niterations. We instead insert a single LookaheadModule between the\naudio bottleneck and the causal separator. It partitions time into nonoverlapping chunks of length S and applies a bidirectional LSTM\nindependently within each chunk; the output is projected, layernormalized, and added as a residual. Because no recurrent state\ncrosses chunk boundaries, the maximum future context is\nlookaheadmax = (S − 1) H,\n\n(1)\n\nwhere H is the STFT hop. The separator remains strictly causal, so no\nadditional lookahead accumulates. We use a two-layer bidirectional\n\nLSTM with 128 hidden units per direction on the 256-channel\nbottleneck. With S = 11 and H = 128 samples (8 ms/frame), the\nmaximum lookahead is 80 ms.\nUnder the challenge latency definition, the algorithmic latency is\nthe 8 ms STFT delay plus the 80 ms lookahead, yielding 88 ms;\nincluding the 8 ms hop buffer gives 96 ms total system latency.\nThe streaming schedule emits one hop after the corresponding\nbounded-lookahead chunk is available, and no recurrent state carries\nfuture information across chunks. A tail-perturbation probe reported\neffective lookaheads of 37.9, 75.0, and 22.6 ms at three positions, all\nbelow the structural bound in Eq. (1); these spot checks supplement,\nbut do not replace, the architectural latency bound.\nB. Offline track: USEF-TFGridNet\nFor Track 2, we use full-context modeling with a USEF-style\nTFGridNet extractor [21], [22]. Rather than compressing the enrollment into a fixed-dimensional speaker embedding, the model\nkeeps frame-level enrollment features and conditions the mixture\nthrough per-frequency cross-attention, with mixture frames as queries\nand effective enrollment frames as keys and values. Since padded\nenrollment frames are excluded from the keys and values, conditioning is invariant to in-batch padding. The target-aware representation\nis concatenated with the mixture representation, processed by six\nGridNetV2 blocks, and decoded by a transposed convolution followed\nby an inverse STFT. The model uses a 256-point window, a 128sample hop, a shared encoder with C = 128 channels, four attention\nheads, and GridNetV2 blocks with hidden dimension 256.\nAfter extraction, we apply a validation-tuned magnitude-domain\nfusion to balance perceptual quality and speaker fidelity. Let xr , xe ∈\nRN denote the original extractor output and the output after a frozen\nRE-USE [16] enhancer for the same sample. The enhanced output\nsuppresses noise but can attenuate the target, whereas the original\noutput preserves target-speaker cues but retains residual noise. We\ntherefore align RMS, fuse STFT magnitudes, and reuse the phase of\nxr .\nSpecifically, we first align the RMS of the enhanced output to that\nof the original output:\n\u0012\n\u0013\nrms(xr )\nx̃e = g xe , g = clip\n, 0.1, 10 .\n(2)\nrms(xe )\nLet Xr = STFT(xr ) and Xe = STFT(x̃e ), with magnitudes\nMr = |Xr | and Me = |Xe |. We estimate frame-level speech activity\nfrom the enhanced magnitude:\n!\ns\nt +ϵ\n20 log10 pe20\n−τ\n1 X\n+ϵ\n2\net =\nMe (f, t) , at = σ\n, (3)\nF\n∆\nf\n\nwhere p20 is the 20th-percentile energy of {et }, τ = 10 dB is the\nactivity threshold above this floor, ∆ = 6 dB controls the sigmoid\ntransition width, and ϵ is a small constant. We smooth at with a 5frame moving average to obtain ãt , and compute the fused magnitude\nas\nwt = w − ρãt ,\n\nMf (f, t) = wt Me (f, t) + (1 − wt )Mr (f, t).\n(4)\nHere w is the background-frame enhancement weight and ρ reduces\nthis weight on speech-active frames. We use validation-tuned values\nw = 0.9 and ρ = 0.35, so active frames retain more of the\noriginal TSE magnitude (w − ρ = 0.55) while background frames\nremain closer to the enhanced magnitude. The final waveform is\nreconstructed as\nx̂ = iSTFT(Mf exp (j∠Xr )) .\n\n(5)\n\n\fIV. T RAINING S ETUP\nBoth systems were trained with the same protocol: gradient clipping at norm 5.0 and a plateau learning-rate scheduler (decay factor\n0.5) driven by the scale-invariant SNR on a validation set of heldout meetings with scenes disjoint from training. Checkpoint selection\nand early stopping both followed this validation metric, avoiding any\ntuning with leaderboard feedback.\nThe track-specific configurations differed in supervision and optimizer. SwiftNet-Lookahead minimized a plain SNR loss against the\ntarget speech, with its ResNet-34 speaker encoder frozen, and was\ntrained on six GPUs with AdamW (initial learning rate 10−3 , weight\ndecay 0.1). USEF-TFGridNet used a combined SNR loss weighting\nthe noisy real target by 0.8 and the cleaned mirror by 0.2, and was\noptimized by Adam [23] with an initial learning rate of 5 × 10−4 .\nAll external corpora and frozen checkpoints used by the submission\nare named in Sections II–III; no development or evaluation split is\nused for training, fine-tuning, or data augmentation.\nV. R ESULTS\nEvaluation protocol. The evaluation set comprises EVAL-1 (2000\n“seen” mixture–enrollment pairs drawn without overlap from the development corpora) and EVAL-2 (3000 “unseen” real-world samples\nnewly recorded across meeting rooms, cafés, homes, and vehicles\nwith near-field, far-field, and mobile devices). Each pair was processed independently with all metadata withheld. The leaderboard\nscores four metrics: target-speaker error rate (TER; lower is better),\npresence-timing F1, speaker similarity (SIM, cosine), and DNSMOS\n[24] perceptual quality. The official rank is the average dense rank\nover these four metrics on the combined EVAL-1+EVAL-2 target;\nthe public leaderboard1 listed 28 Track 1 participants and 35 Track 2\nparticipants at our final snapshot [5].\nOnline track. Table II reports Track 1. On the public leaderboard\nsnapshot, SwiftNet-Lookahead ranks second overall among valid\nparticipants. The table compares it with the two official BSRNN\nbaselines [25]; SwiftNet-Lookahead leads both on all four metrics.\nThe ablation in Table III explains two design choices. For training\ndata, the mixed setting attains the best TER, Timing F1, and SIM;\nsynthetic-only data degrades the most (TER 0.857, DNSMOS 1.676),\nsuggesting that real acoustics are important for generalization, while\nreal-only data reaches a marginally higher DNSMOS but trails on\nintelligibility and similarity, being limited in scale and scene diversity.\nFor the enrollment encoder, ResNet-34 gives the best TER and the\nbest DNSMOS; TF-MAP/contextual embedding [26] matches it on\nTiming F1 and SIM but drops sharply to 1.923 DNSMOS, and\nECAPA-TDNN [27] is comparable on TER yet weaker elsewhere. We\ntherefore adopt mixed training data with the ResNet-34 conditioning\nrepresentation.\nTABLE II\nO NLINE TRACK (T RACK 1).\n\nSystem\n\nTER↓ Timing F1↑ SIM↑ DNSMOS↑\n\nSwiftNet-Lookahead (ours) 0.719\nBSRNN-TFMAP\n0.805\nBSRNN-EMB\n0.809\n\n0.847\n0.836\n0.821\n\n0.480\n0.456\n0.422\n\n2.399\n1.670\n1.714\n\nOffline track. Table IV reports Track 2. USEF-TFGridNet ranks\nfifth on the public snapshot and beats both baselines by a large margin\n(TER 0.680, DNSMOS 2.484). Its remaining speaker-similarity gap\nis consistent with the perception-distortion trade-off from fusing\n1 https://leaderboard.real-tse.com/\n\nTABLE III\nA BLATION STUDY OF S WIFT N ET-L OOKAHEAD .\n\nConfiguration\n\nTER↓ Timing F1↑ SIM↑ DNSMOS↑\n\nTraining-data composition\nMixed synthetic + real (default) 0.719\nSynthetic data only\n0.857\nReal data only\n0.739\n\n0.847\n0.839\n0.841\n\n0.480\n0.454\n0.450\n\n2.399\n1.676\n2.477\n\nEnrollment audio encoder\nResNet-34 (default)\n0.719\nECAPA-TDNN\n0.723\nTF-MAP/contextual embedding 0.757\n\n0.847\n0.828\n0.848\n\n0.480\n0.464\n0.483\n\n2.399\n2.392\n1.923\n\ntoward denoised magnitudes on background frames [28]. Table V\nshows that frame-level enrollment cross-attention gives the best TER\nand DNSMOS, whereas compressed embeddings have similar Timing\nF1/SIM but worse perceptual quality. Within the supervision-weight\nblock, 0.8:0.2 is best on all metrics; a small cleaned-mirror weight\nbalances fidelity to real acoustics against residual-noise suppression.\nTABLE IV\nO FFLINE TRACK (T RACK 2).\n\nSystem\n\nTER↓ Timing F1↑ SIM↑ DNSMOS↑\n\nUSEF-TFGridNet (ours)\n0.680\nBSRNN-EMB (baseline)\n0.829\nBSRNN-TFMAP (baseline) 0.838\n\n0.851\n0.829\n0.829\n\n0.471\n0.417\n0.443\n\n2.484\n1.844\n1.612\n\nTABLE V\nA BLATION STUDY OF USEF-TFG RID N ET.\n\nConfiguration\n\nTER↓ Timing F1↑ SIM↑ DNSMOS↑\n\nEnrollment audio encoder\nUSEF (default)\n0.680\nResNet-34\n0.739\nECAPA-TDNN\n0.728\nTF-MAP/contextual embedding 0.781\n\n0.851\n0.853\n0.850\n0.845\n\n0.471\n0.474\n0.476\n0.470\n\n2.484\n1.903\n2.248\n2.138\n\nCombined supervision weight (noisy real target:cleaned mirror target)\n0:1\n0.756\n0.844\n0.454\n2.271\n0.5 : 0.5\n0.739\n0.841\n0.450\n2.477\n0.8 : 0.2 (default)\n0.680\n0.851\n0.471\n2.484\n1:0\n0.684\n0.840\n0.452\n2.249\n\nVI. C ONCLUSION\nThis paper presents the SonicAGI systems for the online and offline\ntracks of the REAL-TSE Challenge. The results suggest that real\nconversational TSE depends not only on separator design, but also\non training-data realism and target construction. Our two-route data\npipeline combines controllable synthetic mixtures with real meeting\noverlap, and uses a cleaned mirror target to reduce the effect of\nresidual background noise in real recordings. SwiftNet-Lookahead\nconfines future context to a single bounded injection, achieving\nsecond place in Track 1 with 96 ms total system latency. USEFTFGridNet combines frame-level enrollment cross-attention with\nmagnitude-domain fusion, ranking fifth in Track 2 while improving\nintelligibility and perceptual quality. The main remaining limitation is\nthe trade-off between speaker similarity and perceptual quality; future\nwork will explore similarity-aware training or fusion objectives and\nextend bounded lookahead to stronger cross-attention extractors.\n\n\fAI-G ENERATED C ONTENT D ISCLOSURE\nChatGPT was used to assist with language editing, grammar refinement, and concision of the manuscript text. The authors reviewed\nand revised all AI-assisted edits.\nR EFERENCES\n[1] S. Wang, Z. Chen, K. A. Lee, Y. Qian, and H. Li, “Overview of\nspeaker modeling and its applications: From the lens of deep speaker\nrepresentation learning,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and\nLanguage Processing, vol. 32, pp. 4971–4998, 2024.\n[2] K. Li, G. Chen, W. Sang, Y. Luo, Z. Chen, S. Wang, S. He, Z.-Q.\nWang, A. Li, Z. Wu et al., “Advances in speech separation: Techniques,\nchallenges, and future trends,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2508.10830, 2025.\n[3] K. Li, K. Gao, and X. Hu, “Efficient audio-visual speech separation\nwith discrete lip semantics and multi-scale global-local attention,” arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2509.23610, 2025.\n[4] K. Li, J. Cheng, C. Zeng, Z. Yan, H. Wang, Z. Su, B. Zheng, and\nX. Hu, “A semantically consistent dataset for data-efficient query-based\nuniversal sound separation,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2601.22599, 2026.\n[5] REAL-TSE Challenge Organizers, “REAL-TSE Challenge: Realworld Target Speaker Extraction Challenge,” https://real-tse.github.io/\nchallenge/, 2026, a satellite challenge of IEEE Spoken Language Technology Workshop (SLT) 2026. Accessed: 2026-06-29.\n[6] Y. Fu, L. Cheng, S. Lv, Y. Jv, Y. Kong, Z. Chen, Y. Hu, L. Xie, J. Wu,\nH. Bu, X. Xu, J. Du, and J. Chen, “AISHELL-4: An open source dataset\nfor speech enhancement, separation, recognition and speaker diarization\nin conference scenario,” in Annual Conference of the International\nSpeech Communication Association (Interspeech), 2021, pp. 3665–3669.\n[7] F. Yu, S. Zhang, Y. Fu, L. Xie, S. Zheng, Z. Du, W. Huang, P. Guo,\nZ. Yan, B. Ma, X. Xu, and H. Bu, “M2MeT: The ICASSP 2022\nmulti-channel multi-party meeting transcription challenge,” in IEEE\nInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n(ICASSP), 2022, pp. 6167–6171.\n[8] J. Carletta, S. Ashby, S. Bourban, M. Flynn, M. Guillemot, T. Hain,\nJ. Kadlec, V. Karaiskos, W. Kraaij, M. Kronenthal, G. Lathoud, M. Lincoln, A. Lisowska, I. McCowan, W. Post, D. Reidsma, and P. Wellner,\n“The AMI meeting corpus: A pre-announcement,” in Machine Learning\nfor Multimodal Interaction. Springer Berlin Heidelberg, 2006, pp. 28–\n39.\n[9] M. Van Segbroeck, A. Zaid, K. Kutsenko, C. Huerta, T. Nguyen,\nX. Luo, B. Hoffmeister, J. Trmal, M. Omologo, and R. Maas, “DiPCo –\ndinner party corpus,” in Annual Conference of the International Speech\nCommunication Association (Interspeech), 2020, pp. 434–438.\n[10] S. Watanabe, M. Mandel, J. Barker, E. Vincent, A. Arora, X. Chang,\nS. Khudanpur, V. Manohar, D. Povey, D. Raj, D. Snyder, A. S. Subramanian, J. Trmal, B. B. Yair, C. Boeddeker, Z. Ni, Y. Fujita, S. Horiguchi,\nN. Kanda, T. Yoshioka, and N. Ryant, “CHiME-6 challenge: Tackling\nmultispeaker speech recognition for unsegmented recordings,” in 6th\nInternational Workshop on Speech Processing in Everyday Environments\n(CHiME 2020), 2020, pp. 1–7.\n[11] T. Afouras, J. S. Chung, and A. Zisserman, “LRS3-TED: A large-scale\ndataset for visual speech recognition,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1809.00496,\n2018.\n[12] J. S. Chung, A. Nagrani, and A. Zisserman, “VoxCeleb2: Deep speaker\nrecognition,” in Annual Conference of the International Speech Communication Association (Interspeech), 2018, pp. 1086–1090.\n[13] G. Wichern, J. Antognini, M. Flynn, L. R. Zhu, E. McQuinn, D. Crow,\nE. Manilow, and J. L. Roux, “WHAM!: Extending speech separation to\nnoisy environments,” in Annual Conference of the International Speech\nCommunication Association (Interspeech), 2019, pp. 1368–1372.\n[14] Y. Luo and J. Yu, “FRA-RIR: Fast random approximation of the imagesource method,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2208.04101, 2022.\n[15] K. Li, W. Sang, C. Zeng, R. Yang, G. Chen, and X. Hu, “Sonicsim:\nA customizable simulation platform for speech processing in moving\nsound source scenarios,” in International Conference on Learning Representations, vol. 2025, 2025, pp. 67 379–67 405.\n[16] S.-W. Fu, R. Chao, X. Yang, S.-F. Huang, R. E. Zezario, R. Nasretdinov,\nA. Jukić, Y. Tsao, and Y.-C. F. Wang, “Rethinking training targets,\narchitectures and data quality for universal speech enhancement,” arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2603.02641, 2026.\n[17] W. Sang, K. Li, R. Yang, J. Huang, and X. Hu, “A fast and lightweight\nmodel for causal audio-visual speech separation,” in European Conference on Artificial Intelligence (ECAI), 2025.\n\n[18] K. He, X. Zhang, S. Ren, and J. Sun, “Deep residual learning for\nimage recognition,” in IEEE Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern\nRecognition (CVPR), 2016, pp. 770–778.\n[19] H. Wang, C. Liang, S. Wang, Z. Chen, B. Zhang, X. Xiang, Y. Deng,\nand Y. Qian, “WeSpeaker: A research and production oriented speaker\nembedding learning toolkit,” in IEEE International Conference on\nAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2023.\n[20] E. Perez, F. Strub, H. de Vries, V. Dumoulin, and A. Courville, “FiLM:\nVisual reasoning with a general conditioning layer,” in AAAI Conference\non Artificial Intelligence (AAAI), 2018.\n[21] B. Zeng and M. Li, “USEF-TSE: Universal speaker embedding free\ntarget speaker extraction,” IEEE Transactions on Audio, Speech and\nLanguage Processing, vol. 33, pp. 2110–2124, 2025.\n[22] Z.-Q. Wang, S. Cornell, S. Choi, Y. Lee, B.-Y. Kim, and S. Watanabe, “TF-GridNet: Integrating full- and sub-band modeling for speech\nseparation,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language\nProcessing, vol. 31, pp. 3221–3236, 2023.\n[23] D. P. Kingma and J. Ba, “Adam: A method for stochastic optimization,”\nin International Conference on Learning Representations (ICLR), 2015.\n[24] C. K. A. Reddy, V. Gopal, and R. Cutler, “DNSMOS: A non-intrusive\nperceptual objective speech quality metric to evaluate noise suppressors,”\nin IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal\nProcessing (ICASSP), 2021, pp. 6493–6497.\n[25] Y. Luo and J. Yu, “Music source separation with band-split RNN,”\nIEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing,\nvol. 31, pp. 1893–1901, 2023.\n[26] K. Zhang, J. Li, S. Wang, Y. Wei, Y. Wang, Y. Wang, and H. Li, “Multilevel speaker representation for target speaker extraction,” in IEEE\nInternational Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n(ICASSP), 2025.\n[27] B. Desplanques, J. Thienpondt, and K. Demuynck, “ECAPA-TDNN:\nEmphasized channel attention, propagation and aggregation in TDNN\nbased speaker verification,” in Annual Conference of the International\nSpeech Communication Association (Interspeech), 2020, pp. 3830–3834.\n[28] Y. Blau and T. Michaeli, “The perception-distortion tradeoff,” in IEEE\nConference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (CVPR), 2018,\npp. 6228–6237.\n\n\f", "numLines": 569, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 569}}}
